#Text=John Stockwood
#Text=John Stockwood ( died 1610 ) was an English clergyman , preacher , translator of Protestant texts and school-master .
#Text=Life

#Text=He was from Kent , and was a pensioner of St John 's College , Cambridge , when Queen Elizabeth visited the university in August 1564 , matriculating on 4 October in that year , and admitted a scholar on the Lady Margaret 's foundation on 10 November following .

#Text=He graduated B.A. in the university of Heidelberg in 1567 , and was incorporated in that degree at Oxford on 19 May 1575 ; [ 1 ] when he stated that he was about to open a ' Indus literarius ' at Cambridge .
#Text=He was admitted M.A. at Oxford on 9 July 1575 , and was incorporated in that degree at Cambridge in 1579 .
#Text=In 1571 he occurs as minister of Battle , Sussex .
#Text=He was appointed headmaster of Tonbridge School , Kent , by the Skinners ' Company of London , a position he held from 1578 to 1588 . [ 2 ]
#Text=It is supposed that Sir Robert Heath was one of his pupils .
#Text=He was a celebrated and powerful preacher , and obtained the vicarage of Tonbridge .

#Text=He was one of the select groups of Puritans ( with Laurence Chaderton , George Gifford , Laurence Humphrey , John Knewstub , Thomas Sampson , and Henry Smith ) who preached at Paul 's Cross . [ 3 ]
#Text=His style was very plain , in common with Bartimaeus Andrewes , Chaderton , Gifford , Stephen Egerton , William Fulke , William Perkins , and Hugh Roberts . [ 4 ]
#Text=He had strong Sabbatarian views , [ 5 ] was one of the Puritan critics of the theatre , [ 6 ] and took particular exception to semi-nude dancing . [ 7 ]
#Text=He also felt schooling paid too much attention to classical authors . [ 8 ]
#Text=At one period he was in great poverty .

#Text=The records of the corporation of Gravesend show that on 30 August 1594 he received a contribution of forty shillings out of the stock of the chamber of that town , requested by Sir Robert Sidney .
#Text=He had ceased to be master of Tonbridge School by 1597 , when his textbook Progymnasma Scholasticum was published .
#Text=In the dedication of that work to Robert Devereux , 2nd Earl of Essex he acknowledges his kindness in relieving his poverty and protecting him from antagonists .
#Text=It is believed that he retained the vicarage of Tonbridge till his death .
#Text=He was buried there on 27 July 1610 .
#Text=Jonathan Stockwood of St. John 's College , Cambridge ( B. A. 1606 , M. A. 1609 ) , may have been his son .
#Text=Works
#Text=His principal works , mainly translations of devotional works by continental reformers , are
#Text=Common Places of Christian Religion , London , 1572 , 1581 ; translated from the Latin of Henry Bullinger , and dedicated to Henry , Earl of Huntingdon .
#Text=The Treasure of Trueth . . . newlie turned into English , London [ 1576 ] ; from the Latin of Theodore Beza ; another edition 1581 .
#Text=A Shorte . . .
#Text=Treatize of the Plague
#Text=, London , 1580 ; translated from the Latin of Theodore Beza , and dedicated to Sir Henry Sidney .
#Text=A Short Catechisme for House Houlders .
#Text=With prayers to the same adjoyning [ by Edward Dering , B.D. ] . . .
#Text=Gathered by J.S.
#Text=, London , 1582 and 1583 .

#Text=Of the Duetie of a Faithful and Wise Magistrate , in preserving and delivering of the comon wealth from infection in the time of the Plague or Pestilence , London , 1583 ; translated from the Latin ( 1582 ) of Johannes Ewich .
#Text=A verie profitable and necessarie discourse concerning the observation and keeping of the Sabbath day , London , 1584 ; translated from the Latin of Zacharias Ursinus .
#Text=A verie godlie and profitable sermon of the necessitie , properties , and office of a good magistrate ( 1584 ) .
#Text=A Right Godly . . . discourse upon the book of Ester , London , 1584 ; from the Latin of John Brentius ; dedicated to Sir Francis Walsingham .

#Text=A godlie and learned Commentarie upon the excellent book of Solomon , commonly called Ecclesiastes , or the Preacher , London , 1585 ; translated from the Latin of Joannes Serranus ( Jean de Serres ) .
#Text=An exposition of the 51 Psalme , by Wolph .
#Text=Musculus , translated
#Text=, London , 1586 ; from Wolfgang Musculus .

#Text=A Bartholmew Fairing for parentes , to bestow vpon their sonnes and daughters , and for one friend to giue vnto another ; shewing that children are not to marie without the consent of their parentes , London , 1589 .

#Text=A plaine and easie laying open of the Meaning and Vnderstanding of the Rules of Construction in the English Accidence , appointed by authentic to be taught in all schooles of hir Maiesties dominions , for the great vse and benefite of young beginners , London , 1590 ; 1703 .
#Text=A fruitfull Commentarie upon the twelve Small Prophets , Cambridge , 1594 ; translated from the Latin of Lambert Danaeus , and dedicated to the Earl and Countess of Huntingdon .
#Text=Progymnasma Scholasticum . Hoc est , Epigrammatum Graecorum ex Anthologia selectorum ab He .
#Text=Stephano duplicique ejusdem interpretatione explicatorum Praxis Grammatica
#Text=, London , 1597 ; dedicated to the Earl of Essex .
#Text=Disputatiuncularum grammaticalium libellus , ad puerorum in scholis triuialibus exacuenda ingenia excogitatus , London , 1598 ; 4th edit ; again 1650 .
